{"uri":"Isolation-and-life-cycle-characterization-of-lytic-dxq7mv","version_id":"0","protocol_name":"Isolation and life cycle characterization of lytic viruses infecting heterotrophic bacteria and cyanobacteria","protocol_name_html":"Isolation and life cycle characterization of lytic viruses infecting heterotrophic bacteria and cyanobacteria","is_prepublished":"0","can_edit":"0","parent_id":null,"api_version":"1","is_new_mode":"0","last_modified":"1516341603","type_id":"3","link":null,"fork_id":"","public_fork_note":"","number_of_steps":"11","has_versions":"0","first_published_date":"1454969332","publish_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:52","documents":null,"have_protocol_in_step":"0","is_protocol_in_step":"0","vendor_name":"Contributed by users","vendor_link":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io","vendor_logo":"\/img\/vendors\/1.png","mod_mins":"-45","mod_secs":"1","description":"This collection presents some of the most widely used methodological approaches for isolation and purification of bacteriophages and cyanophages, the first step in detailed studies of virus\u2013host interactions and viral genetic composition, and discusses the applications and limitations of different isolation procedures. Most work on phage isolation has been carried out with aerobic heterotrophic bacteria and cyanobacteria, culturable both on agar plates and in enriched liquid cultures. The procedures presented here are limited to lytic viruses infecting such hosts. In addition to the isolation procedures, methods for life cycle characterization (one-step growth experiments) of bacteriophages and cyanophages are described.","is_bookmarked":"0","can_reassign":"1","before_start":null,"has_guidelines":"0","materials":[],"warning":null,"version_class":"1744","public":"1","is_owner":"1","is_original_owner":"1","created_on":"1444075524","protocol_affiliation":"","affiliation":null,"doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dxq7mv","doi_status":"2","changed_fork_steps":null,"profile_url":"w2v2b433v2","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","full_name":"Amy Chan","created_by":"Amy Chan","private_link":"738C668E08E0538604E3289E439B7379","original_img":"1","username":"amy-chan","is_retracted":"0","retraction_reason":null,"plos_id":null,"manuscript_citation":null,"journal_name":null,"is_donations_disabled":"0","is_donations_disabled_by_user":"9","item_record_id":222880,"fork_info":[],"compare_forks":[],"protocols":[{"protocol_name":"Bacteriophage isolation by spotting on target host cells","protocol_name_html":"Bacteriophage isolation by spotting on target host cells","protocol_id":"1490","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1521957601","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"12","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"132","uri":"Bacteriophage-isolation-by-spotting-on-target-host-dps5nd","description":"Phage lysis of host bacteria can be visualized by plaque formation on lawns of host cells in soft agar overlayed on agar plates (Adams, 1959; Sambrook et al. 1989). This principle can be used for the detection and subsequent isolation of specific lytic phages in environmental samples (e.g., Carlson 2005). Spotting environmental samples on lawns of a target host cell would thus reveal the presence of a lytic phage for that particular host cell in the given sample.","public":"1","created_on":"1441045598","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:52","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dps5nd","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_uri":"suttle-laboratory-of-marine-molecular-microbiology","group_name":"Suttle Laboratory of Marine Molecular Microbiology and Virology","group_logo":"","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"}],"versions":[{"protocol_id":"1490","protocol_name":"Bacteriophage isolation by spotting on target host cells","protocol_name_html":"Bacteriophage isolation by spotting on target host cells","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","user_id":"0","uri":"Bacteriophage-isolation-by-spotting-on-target-host-dps5nd","version_id":"0","date_created":"2015-08-31 18:26:38","created_on":"1441045598","published_on":"1454969332","full_name":"Amy Chan","username":"amy-chan","affiliation":null,"profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","has_access":"1"}],"forks_count":{"public":"0","private":"0"}},{"protocol_name":"Bacteriophage isolation using enrichment cultures","protocol_name_html":"Bacteriophage isolation using enrichment cultures","protocol_id":"1491","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1522216802","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"8","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"79","uri":"Bacteriophage-isolation-using-enrichment-cultures-dpt5nm","description":"A generally more efficient way of isolating lytic phages from marine environments is by the use of enrichment cultures. In this approach, the prefiltered water sample that is to be screened for phages against a given target bacterium, is enriched with a bacterial growth medium and amended with that target bacteria (Eisenstark 1967; Carlson 2005). This allows any lytic phages present in the sample to infect the target bacteria and propagate in the cultures, and subsequently, be isolated and purified. The two main advantages of the enrichment approach are 1) that it allows for screening for phages in a much larger volume of sample (typically 25\u201350 mL, rather than 5\u201310 \u00b5L), thus increasing the probability of isolating rare phages, and 2) that it allows the combination of different target hosts (e.g., different strains of a specific bacteria of interest) in the same incubation, again increasing the possibility of phage isolation.","public":"1","created_on":"1441050639","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:54","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dpt5nm","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_uri":"suttle-laboratory-of-marine-molecular-microbiology","group_name":"Suttle Laboratory of Marine Molecular Microbiology and Virology","group_logo":"","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"}],"versions":[{"protocol_id":"1491","protocol_name":"Bacteriophage isolation using enrichment cultures","protocol_name_html":"Bacteriophage isolation using enrichment cultures","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","user_id":"0","uri":"Bacteriophage-isolation-using-enrichment-cultures-dpt5nm","version_id":"0","date_created":"2015-08-31 19:50:39","created_on":"1441050639","published_on":"1454969334","full_name":"Amy Chan","username":"amy-chan","affiliation":null,"profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","has_access":"1"}],"forks_count":{"public":"0","private":"0"}},{"protocol_name":"Obtaining pure phage stock","protocol_name_html":"Obtaining pure phage stock","protocol_id":"1492","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1510247633","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"7","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"25","uri":"Obtaining-pure-phage-stock-dpu5nv","description":"Clearing zones on lawns of host bacteria potentially contain all lytic phages against the given host that were present in the original water sample. Little is still known about the occurrence and diversity of phages infecting specific hosts, but generally isolation procedures as those described above may reveal multiple phages against specific target bacteria (e.g., Comeau et al. 2006; Holmfeldt et al. 2007; Stenholm et al. 2008). It is therefore necessary to further isolate the phages to obtain specific stocks of single phages.","public":"1","created_on":"1441052262","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:54","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dpu5nv","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_uri":"suttle-laboratory-of-marine-molecular-microbiology","group_name":"Suttle Laboratory of Marine Molecular Microbiology and Virology","group_logo":"","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"}],"versions":[{"protocol_id":"1492","protocol_name":"Obtaining pure phage stock","protocol_name_html":"Obtaining pure phage stock","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","user_id":"0","uri":"Obtaining-pure-phage-stock-dpu5nv","version_id":"0","date_created":"2015-08-31 20:17:42","created_on":"1441052262","published_on":"1454969334","full_name":"Amy Chan","username":"amy-chan","affiliation":null,"profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","has_access":"1"}],"forks_count":{"public":"0","private":"0"}},{"protocol_name":"One-step growth experiments (bacteriophages)","protocol_name_html":"One-step growth experiments (bacteriophages)","protocol_id":"1494","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1522044002","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"13","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"79","uri":"One-step-growth-experiments-bacteriophages-dpw5pd","description":"The life cycle of phages can be characterized by one-step growth experiments, which are designed in a way that allows only a single infection cycle to take place (i.e., no re-infections occurring by phages produced during the experiment).","public":"1","created_on":"1441054131","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:55","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"1","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dpw5pd","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_uri":"suttle-laboratory-of-marine-molecular-microbiology","group_name":"Suttle Laboratory of Marine Molecular Microbiology and Virology","group_logo":"","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"}],"versions":[{"protocol_id":"1494","protocol_name":"One-step growth experiments (bacteriophages)","protocol_name_html":"One-step growth experiments (bacteriophages)","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","user_id":"0","uri":"One-step-growth-experiments-bacteriophages-dpw5pd","version_id":"0","date_created":"2015-08-31 20:48:51","created_on":"1441054131","published_on":"1454969335","full_name":"Amy Chan","username":"amy-chan","affiliation":null,"profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","has_access":"1"}],"forks_count":{"public":"0","private":"1"}},{"protocol_name":"Isolation of cyanophages by liquid bioassays","protocol_name_html":"Isolation of cyanophages by liquid bioassays","protocol_id":"1498","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1522216802","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"20","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"33","uri":"Isolation-of-cyanophages-by-liquid-bioassays-dp25qd","description":"Multiwell plates are convenient for isolating cyanophages from environmental samples using the liquid bioassay approach (Table 1). This protocol describes\u00a0a typical procedure (96-well assay) used to detect and isolate cyanophages from marine samples that lyses <em>Synechococcus<\/em> sp. strain DC2 (also known as CCMP1334 or WH7803). Using this method, greater than 10<sup>5<\/sup> lytic phages per milliliter of seawater have been detected in the Gulf of Mexico (Suttle and Chan 1994) that lyses this permissive target host.","public":"1","created_on":"1441134606","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:55","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/1