ses. Similar to the use of enrichment cultures for bacteriophages, the disadvantages include the fact that lysis of the host cells are not always obvious, especially if the initial titer is low or if the host culture is not clonal or unialgal.","public":"1","created_on":"1441142969","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:55","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dp65rd","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_uri":"suttle-laboratory-of-marine-molecular-microbiology","group_name":"Suttle Laboratory of Marine Molecular Microbiology and Virology","group_logo":"","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"}],"versions":[{"protocol_id":"1502","protocol_name":"Isolation of cyanophages by liquid enrichment assay","protocol_name_html":"Isolation of cyanophages by liquid enrichment assay","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","user_id":"0","uri":"Isolation-of-cyanophages-by-liquid-enrichment-assa-dp65rd","version_id":"0","date_created":"2015-09-01 21:29:29","created_on":"1441142969","published_on":"1454969335","full_name":"Amy Chan","username":"amy-chan","affiliation":null,"profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","has_access":"1"}],"forks_count":{"public":"0","private":"0"}},{"protocol_name":"Isolation of cyanophages by plaque assays","protocol_name_html":"Isolation of cyanophages by plaque assays","protocol_id":"1512","version_id":"0","last_modified":"1510247633","link":"http:\/\/www.aslo.org\/books\/mave\/MAVE_118.pdf","fork_id":null,"number_of_steps":"20","vendor_id":"1","downloads":"0","views":"46","uri":"Isolation-of-cyanophages-by-plaque-assays-dqg5tv","description":"More than 40 years ago, Safferman and Morris (1963) used the plaque assay method to isolate the first cyanophage that infects a freshwater filamentous cyanobacterium, <em>Plectonema boryanum<\/em>. Since then, this approach has been used successfully to detect and isolate a number of different phages infecting marine<em> Synechoccocus<\/em> and <em>Prochlorococcus<\/em> (e.g., Suttle and Chan 1993; Waterbury and Valois 1993; Wilson et al. 1993; Sullivan et al. 2003).<br \/><br \/>The advantages of this method are that results are easily interpreted as plaques formed on pigmented lawns can be easily identified. Since a plaque is the result of a single infection event, the virus can be easily purified and cloned.\u00a0The first part of the procedures described as follows: (1) preparation of base plates and (2) preparation of top agar\/agarose are applicable also for bacteriophage plaque assays.","public":"1","created_on":"1441214404","first_published_date":"2016-02-08 22:08:56","authors":"Mathias Middelboe, Amy M. Chan, and Sif K. Bertelsen","has_guidelines":"1","has_warning":"0","has_before_start":"0","protocol_affiliation":"Manual of Aquatic Viral Ecology","doi":"dx.doi.org\/10.17504\/protocols.io.dqg5tv","doi_status":"2","type_id":"1","created_by":"Amy Chan","is_bookmarked":"0","affiliation":null,"username":"amy-chan","first_name":"Amy","last_name":"Chan","profile_image":"\/img\/avatars\/016.png","protocol_img":"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/img\/default_protocol.png","groups":[{"group_id":"45","group_uri":"verve-net","group_name":"VERVE Net","group_logo":"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/pr-journal\/cdqcwwe.png","requested_uid":null,"request_flag":null,"my_request":"1"},{"group_id":"81","group_